<exercise id="exercise-23">
<problem id="idp6379600">
<para id="element-24">
A person jumps off from a wall of height “h” with a small box of mass “m” on his head. What is the normal force applied by the box on his head during the fall?
</para>
<para id="element-25">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mi> (a) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> m </m:mi>
<m:mi> g </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> (b) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> m </m:mi>
<m:mo> ( </m:mo>
<m:mi> a </m:mi>
<m:mo> + </m:mo>
<m:mi> g </m:mi>
<m:mo> ) </m:mo>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> (c) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> m </m:mi>
<m:mo> ( </m:mo>
<m:mi> a </m:mi>
<m:mo> - </m:mo>
<m:mi> g </m:mi>
<m:mo> ) </m:mo>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> (d) </m:mi>
<m:mspace width="4pt"/>
<m:mi> zero </m:mi>
</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</para>
</problem>
<solution id="idp1642656">

<para id="element-26">The motion of the box takes place in relation to the person, who is accelerating down with acceleration “g”. Here, we analyze the problem in the inertial frame of the ground. The forces on the box are (i) its weight, "mg", acting downward and (ii) normal force, "N", acting downward. As the bodies are falling freely under the gravity, the acceleration of each of them is equal to "g" i.e. acceleration due to gravity. 
</para>
<para id="element-27">
Now, the free body diagram of the box is shown in the figure. 
</para>
<para id="element-28">
<figure id="fig-28"><title> Free body diagram </title>
<media id="idp6613520" alt=""><image src="../../media/afq1.gif" mime-type="image/gif"/></media>
</figure>
</para>
<para id="element-29">
<m:math display="block">
<m:mtable columnalign="left">
<m:mtr>
<m:mtd>
<m:mo> ∑ </m:mo>
